177
00:26:45,092 --> 00:26:53,318
[SPEAKER_08]: You were yet another black renaissance, a renaissance for black folk, a glorious black prince out of Africa.

178
00:26:53,378 --> 00:26:57,942
[SPEAKER_08]: More than anything else, you compelled us to do something.

179
00:26:58,663 --> 00:27:05,568
[SPEAKER_08]: To take what we had and what we knew and who we were and just do something.

180
00:27:07,045 --> 00:27:11,586
[SPEAKER_08]: With my good friend Godfrey, my something was the cabaret for freedom.

181
00:27:12,868 --> 00:27:20,952
[SPEAKER_08]: I knew song and dance and how to entertain, and the black elite said, yes, my sister.

182
00:27:22,212 --> 00:27:31,936
[SPEAKER_08]: Sidney Poitier and Ozzie Davis and Ruby Dee and Lorraine Hansberry came out to see us dance and sing and entertain.

183
00:27:33,197 --> 00:27:37,179
[SPEAKER_08]: Every dime that came into the SCLC's coffers, blessed.

184
00:27:37,879 --> 00:27:39,180
[SPEAKER_08]: You thanked me for this.

185
00:27:39,600 --> 00:27:41,620
[SPEAKER_08]: You said you were grateful.

186
00:27:42,681 --> 00:27:49,563
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, I couldn't be Bayard Rustin at SCLC, but you compelled me to do something.

187
00:27:50,704 --> 00:27:58,786
[SPEAKER_08]: I took what I had and what I knew and who I was and did something.

188
00:28:00,427 --> 00:28:04,972
[SPEAKER_08]: I did my best to be useful, to show myself approved.

189
00:28:05,353 --> 00:28:10,178
[SPEAKER_08]: Meeting you face to face was monumental, if not magical.

190
00:28:11,431 --> 00:28:13,192
[SPEAKER_08]: You were shorter than I expected.

191
00:28:13,212 --> 00:28:15,734
[SPEAKER_08]: And so young.

192
00:28:16,775 --> 00:28:19,697
[SPEAKER_08]: You had an easy friendliness which was unsettling.

193
00:28:20,417 --> 00:28:21,077
[SPEAKER_08]: And you were funny.

194
00:28:22,178 --> 00:28:22,498
[SPEAKER_08]: Really.

195
00:28:23,779 --> 00:28:24,660
[SPEAKER_08]: I couldn't stay long.

196
00:28:25,580 --> 00:28:26,381
[SPEAKER_08]: Just as St.

197
00:28:26,441 --> 00:28:32,805
[SPEAKER_08]: Louis ultimately became Harlem, Harlem must ultimately become the new thing and the next thing.

198
00:28:33,846 --> 00:28:36,748
[SPEAKER_08]: Change remains our only constant.

199
00:28:37,853 --> 00:28:42,415
[SPEAKER_08]: In late 1960, I met my own South African freedom fighter.

200
00:28:43,055 --> 00:28:48,117
[SPEAKER_08]: My time to do something evolved into something else.

201
00:28:49,117 --> 00:28:58,561
[SPEAKER_08]: As I left the cocoon of SCLC, I wished you all a year of unlimited success, unlimited strides.

202
00:28:58,721 --> 00:29:05,604
[SPEAKER_08]: I joined with millions of black people all over the world saying, you are our leader.

203
00:29:08,018 --> 00:29:09,519
[SPEAKER_08]: We couldn't want for better.

204
00:29:10,719 --> 00:29:15,022
[SPEAKER_08]: America couldn't want for better.

205
00:29:16,543 --> 00:29:18,584
[SPEAKER_08]: Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.

206
00:29:19,264 --> 00:29:23,466
[SPEAKER_08]: Fair winds and full sails forever.

207
00:29:25,488 --> 00:29:26,248
[SPEAKER_08]: Maya Angelou.

208
00:29:38,792 --> 00:30:00,977
[SPEAKER_08]: Dear Reverend Dr. King, in August 28th of 1963, when about 250,000 people streamed towards the Lincoln Memorial at the March on Washington and the hours before you'd given your magnificent I Have a Dream speech, I was invited to stand with five other women and be recognized on stage during an official tribute to Negro women and freedom fighters in America.

209
00:30:01,958 --> 00:30:07,579
[SPEAKER_08]: Me, Diane Nash Bevel, alongside Rosa Parks and Daisy Bates,

210
00:30:09,145 --> 00:30:12,628
[SPEAKER_08]: In the perfection of hindsight, I regret not being there.

211
00:30:13,508 --> 00:30:23,215
[SPEAKER_08]: James and I decided to watch the ceremony from our motel room in Birmingham, Alabama, eating room service in bed and just trying to rest up for the next big fight.

212
00:30:24,416 --> 00:30:29,760
[SPEAKER_08]: That morning in Birmingham, when people had started to assemble to get on the buses, James said to me,

213
00:30:31,110 --> 00:30:38,974
[SPEAKER_08]: Diane, you know, with everybody having left and gone to Washington, we could get some rest if we stayed here, which just sounded great to me.

214
00:30:39,674 --> 00:30:44,636
[SPEAKER_08]: We'd worked so hard recruiting people to get on the buses that we were exhausted.

215
00:30:45,637 --> 00:30:50,659
[SPEAKER_08]: I didn't know that I was going to be recognized on stage, but we saw the moment on TV.

216
00:30:51,700 --> 00:30:53,360
[SPEAKER_08]: That was such a weird feeling.

217
00:30:53,400 --> 00:30:58,503
[SPEAKER_08]: I felt like reaching towards the television and saying, oh, I can't get there.

218
00:31:00,089 --> 00:31:07,976
[SPEAKER_08]: My first political awakening came in 1959 when I was a college student at Fisk University in Nashville.

219
00:31:08,957 --> 00:31:12,320
[SPEAKER_08]: See, I wanted to come to the South to see what it was really like.

220
00:31:13,481 --> 00:31:15,103
[SPEAKER_08]: And what I saw was eye-opening.

221
00:31:16,103 --> 00:31:18,105
[SPEAKER_08]: I couldn't get takeout at certain restaurants.

222
00:31:18,666 --> 00:31:20,347
[SPEAKER_08]: I couldn't even go to the public library.

223
00:31:20,627 --> 00:31:23,030
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, I know I'm preaching to a preacher here.

224
00:31:23,610 --> 00:31:32,673
[SPEAKER_08]: But very often, people think of segregation before our movement as the notion that you couldn't go into restaurants and that blacks had to ride at the back of buses.

225
00:31:33,993 --> 00:31:35,794
[SPEAKER_08]: But it was so much more than that.

226
00:31:36,794 --> 00:31:38,495
[SPEAKER_08]: Even for us young college students.

227
00:31:39,675 --> 00:31:40,835
[SPEAKER_08]: There were daily insults.

228
00:31:41,796 --> 00:31:45,217
[SPEAKER_08]: A white person could pass you and call you horrible things.

229
00:31:45,777 --> 00:31:49,498
[SPEAKER_08]: And if you dared retaliate or say anything, you could be beaten.

230
00:31:49,938 --> 00:31:51,558
[SPEAKER_08]: or arrested or killed.

231
00:31:51,578 --> 00:31:58,840
[SPEAKER_08]: I just felt outraged when I was trying to learn new things, broaden my horizons.

232
00:31:59,580 --> 00:32:06,822
[SPEAKER_08]: I found segregation just the opposite, limiting, constricting, confining, insulting.

233
00:32:08,102 --> 00:32:17,684
[SPEAKER_08]: Every time I obeyed a segregation rule, I felt like I was agreeing that I was too inferior to use this facility or to go through a front door.

234
00:32:19,366 --> 00:32:23,391
[SPEAKER_08]: The change in me came through James Lawson's workshops on campus.

235
00:32:24,192 --> 00:32:29,459
[SPEAKER_08]: He shared nonviolent movement techniques that he learned from Gandhi in India.

236
00:32:30,500 --> 00:32:35,086
[SPEAKER_08]: I took what I learned and became chairperson of the Student Central Committee.

237
00:32:35,666 --> 00:32:44,633
[SPEAKER_08]: And we planned the 1960 sit-ins that led to Nashville becoming the first southern city to desegregate lunch counters and public facilities.

238
00:32:45,794 --> 00:32:51,018
[SPEAKER_08]: Eventually, I co-founded the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee.

239
00:32:52,720 --> 00:32:55,262
[SPEAKER_08]: My dear friend, John Lewis, was with me then.

240
00:32:56,663 --> 00:32:57,804
[SPEAKER_08]: We thought we could make a difference.

241
00:32:59,096 --> 00:33:01,237
[SPEAKER_08]: Dr. King, I know you know all of this.

242
00:33:02,258 --> 00:33:04,359
[SPEAKER_08]: You've been so gracious in your acknowledgment.

243
00:33:05,399 --> 00:33:13,683
[SPEAKER_08]: In 1962, you said, I was the driving spirit in the nonviolent assault on segregation at lunch counters.

244
00:33:15,804 --> 00:33:20,927
[SPEAKER_08]: Our Freedom Riders were attacked in Alabama on May 14th in 1961.

245
00:33:21,828 --> 00:33:36,796
[SPEAKER_08]: I was one of those folks who decided that the Freedom Rides must continue, and one who organized transportation for members of the Nashville Student Central Committee to go to Alabama to finish the journey that those Freedom Riders started.

246
00:33:37,717 --> 00:33:44,481
[SPEAKER_08]: I wanted to prove that you can't stop a determined nonviolent movement by inflicting violence.

247
00:33:45,762 --> 00:33:49,125
[SPEAKER_08]: It was a lesson about the power of love.

248
00:33:51,026 --> 00:33:56,171
[SPEAKER_08]: You taught me that truth, Dr. King, and I'm in debt for the lesson.

249
00:33:57,938 --> 00:34:07,951
[SPEAKER_08]: My involvement with your march on Washington began shortly after I was arrested for trying to finish the walk for justice started by white postal worker William Moore.

250
00:34:08,832 --> 00:34:13,097
[SPEAKER_08]: His trek ended in Alabama when he was shot dead on April 23, 1963.

251
00:34:16,849 --> 00:34:30,640
[SPEAKER_08]: James came to drive me home to Birmingham after I got out of the jail, and he asked me what I thought of the idea of a national campout on the White House lawn to solidify and insist on the movement's goals.

252
00:34:31,661 --> 00:34:38,987
[SPEAKER_08]: I liked the idea and got started on a meeting to talk about it, inviting attendees, finding a location, and following up on the logistics.

253
00:34:39,468 --> 00:34:44,191
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, you came to that meeting, Dr. King, with some of your team when you left.

254
00:34:44,972 --> 00:34:50,410
[SPEAKER_08]: The notion of planning and organizing that march moved along with you, but I didn't feel left out.

255
00:34:51,491 --> 00:34:54,112
[SPEAKER_08]: I just wanted to see it come to fruition.

256
00:34:54,132 --> 00:34:58,493
[SPEAKER_08]: I spread the word about the march in Birmingham at churches and at the bus stops.

257
00:35:00,294 --> 00:35:14,599
[SPEAKER_08]: The notion of receiving an award for my work in this movement at your monumental march on Washington was the furthest thing from my mind when James and I settled into our hotel room in late August.

258
00:35:15,399 --> 00:35:22,227
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, we'd worked so hard recruiting people to get on the buses and we were just exhausted indeed.

259
00:35:22,247 --> 00:35:29,436
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, the movement has also shown me that a little rest from time to time is surely a good thing.

260
00:35:31,624 --> 00:35:36,005
[SPEAKER_08]: I pray that you will also have time to rest, Dr. King.

261
00:35:37,046 --> 00:35:41,927
[SPEAKER_08]: So much of our hopes and dreams depend on what you're teaching us.

262
00:35:43,328 --> 00:35:48,549
[SPEAKER_08]: We will forever be in your debt for the lessons.

263
00:35:49,970 --> 00:35:56,632
[SPEAKER_08]: Yours, in service and sacrifice, Diane Nash Bevel.

264
00:36:55,277 --> 00:37:02,844
[SPEAKER_10]: So she's here engaged in a serious exercise in American oratory.

265
00:37:03,744 --> 00:37:07,107
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'm over there crying like a baby.

266
00:37:11,771 --> 00:37:13,113
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you so much, Maya.

267
00:37:13,953 --> 00:37:16,335
[SPEAKER_10]: You make your daddy and mommy proud.

268
00:37:24,389 --> 00:37:29,413
[SPEAKER_10]: And I knew when I was writing the letters that you would be perfect for the assignment.

269
00:37:30,714 --> 00:37:37,579
[SPEAKER_10]: And I'm so grateful that you made time to come create community and art with us today.

270
00:37:38,039 --> 00:37:39,240
[SPEAKER_10]: Maya Naomi Cotter.

271
00:37:45,470 --> 00:38:03,265
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, so now if you will indulge the poet in me to dip into my own bag, I'm going to have my piano man and the founder of the Medford Jazz Festival, Jonathan Fagan, join me for a piece that we played together a number of times.

272
00:38:04,025 --> 00:38:15,693
[SPEAKER_10]: In fact, we've recently released an entire CD of music that meets at the intersection of jazz and social justice under the title of The Ally Project.

273
00:38:16,354 --> 00:38:19,376
[SPEAKER_10]: That CD is available today if you're interested.

274
00:38:19,396 --> 00:38:21,818
[SPEAKER_10]: This is a sample of that music.

275
00:38:22,198 --> 00:38:23,759
[SPEAKER_10]: It's called Beloved Country.

